But even in the life of retirement there are and there have been many high-souled men who have been engaged in impor- tant inquiries or embarked on most important enterprises and yet kept themselves within the limits of their own affairs3 or, taking a middle course between philosophers on the one hand and statesmen on the other, they were content with managing their own property—not increasing it by any and every means nor debarring their kindred from the enjoyment of it, but rather, if ever there were need, sharing it with their friends and with the state. Only let it, in the first place, be honestly acquired, by the use of no dishonest or fraudulent means; let it, in the second place, increase by wisdom, industry, and thrift3 and, finally, let it

’ be made available for the use of as many as possible (if only they are worthy) and be at the service of generosity and beneficence rather than of sensuality and excess.

By observing these rules, one may live in magnifi- cence, dignity, and independence, and yet in honour, truth and charity toward all.
